Scottish independent schools have a tradition of academic excellence, which continued in 2018 with another set of outstanding exam results, and additional weight is given by individual and shared successes in sports, art, music and other community activities.
With more than 30,000 students across Scotland, these schools represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS) strive to provide the best level of service to their students and their parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare students for further education and higher education, the career they want and make them citizens of the world.
As an educational sector that can design and implement the aforementioned school curriculum, we see that modern languages continue to be a favorite and desired subject of choice in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, "If you talk to a man in a language he understands, it goes to his head.
If you speak to him in your mother tongue, it goes to his heart."
This statement is a strong reminder that we cannot use only English if we want to build trust and relationships with people from other countries.
The latest results of the final exams this year show that the highest scores in languages were achieved by independent school participants.
A total of 68% of foreign language learners received excellent grades.
The data collected in 74 SCIS member schools show that 72% of students received an excellent score for Mandarin, while 72% of students learning German, 69% of students learning French and 63% of students learning Spanish also received the highest score possible.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as a key skill that children and young people will certainly need in the future.
Nowadays, languages as elective subjects are considered as important as STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in the curriculum of independent schools, as well as in other places.
A survey conducted by the UK Commission on Employment and Skills in 2014 revealed that 17% of employers cannot fill jobs due to a lack of workforce with language skills.
Therefore, language skills are increasingly becoming an imperative for preparing young people for careers.
As more and more jobs are required to know the language, these skills are essential in a globalised world.
Regardless of career choices, people who have learned to speak a foreign language in the future will feel the benefits of such long-term skills.
A person who speaks multiple languages can communicate directly with strangers, and this gives them an advantage over competition.
According to a YouGov survey in 2013 involving more than 4000 adults, 75% of UK respondents do not know a foreign language well enough to be able to communicate in it, and French is the only language spoken by a two-digit percentage of respondents, 15% of them in particular.
Therefore, investing in language learning is very important for today's children.
If children learn more languages, especially the languages of developing countries, they will have more opportunities to find a good job.
In Scotland, every school offers a variety of languages.
Some schools will include classical, modern languages in their program, while others will opt for languages that are considered to be most important in the UK in 2020, for example Mandarin or Japanese.
Regardless of your child's interests, independent schools will always have a diverse selection, as well as teaching staff who are competent in this field.
Scottish independent schools provide children with an environment where they will learn to prepare and arm themselves with the skills they need to succeed, regardless of what the future holds for us.
One cannot ignore the fact that, in today's global business, language knowledge is very important for the future of each country, so this must also be reflected in education.
Therefore, knowledge of modern languages should indeed be seen as "international communication skills".
Independent schools will continue to offer language selection, diversity and excellence to young Scots.
Il faut bien le faire.
John Edward is Director of the Scottish Independent Schools Council
