Then a habitat map and a report will be created to create a detailed picture of their behavior.
Rob Dewar, NTS Nature Protection Advisor, hopes the results will reveal which habitat areas are most important for bats and how each species uses them.
This information will help determine the benefits of working on the management of habitats, such as the creation of meadows and how best to maintain forest areas for bats and other related species.
Bat populations in Scotland and throughout the United Kingdom have declined significantly over the past century.
They are threatened by construction and works on landscaping that affect shelters and habitat loss.
Wind turbines and lighting can also pose a danger, as well as flycatchers and certain chemical treatments of building materials, and pet cat attacks.
Bats are not actually blind.
